---
import BaseLayout from '~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import WordToPdfConverter from '~/components/WordToPdfConverter';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Word to PDF · a → b"
  description="Convert Word documents (.docx) to PDF in your browser with high-fidelity formatting. Files never leave your device."
>
  <header class="mb-8">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">Word → PDF</h1>
    <p class="mt-2 text-lg" style="color: var(--color-muted)">
      Convert Word documents (.docx) to PDF with formatting preserved — entirely in your browser.
    </p>
  </header>

  <WordToPdfConverter client:load />

  <aside
    class="mt-12 space-y-6 rounded-xl border p-6"
    style="border-color: var(--color-border); background: var(--color-accent-soft)"
  >
    <div>
      <h2
        class="mb-2 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wider uppercase"
        style="color: var(--color-accent)"
      >
        How this works
      </h2>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        We render your <code>.docx</code> file in the browser using
        <code>docx-preview</code> — a library specifically designed to preserve Word's visual
        styling (fonts, colors, alignment, tables, headers, footers). Then your browser's
        native print dialog produces a PDF with <strong>selectable text</strong>.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Your file never leaves your device. Verify in DevTools — the Network tab shows zero
        outbound requests during conversion.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h2
        class="mb-2 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wider uppercase"
        style="color: var(--color-accent)"
      >
        What gets preserved
      </h2>
      <ul
        class="ml-5 list-disc space-y-1 text-sm leading-relaxed"
        style="color: var(--color-muted)"
      >
        <li>Font family, size, color, weight (bold/italic)</li>
        <li>Paragraph alignment, spacing, and indentation</li>
        <li>Tables with borders, cell shading, column widths</li>
        <li>Numbered and bulleted lists with correct nesting</li>
        <li>Headers and footers</li>
        <li>Page breaks</li>
        <li>Embedded images (positioning is best-effort)</li>
        <li>Hyperlinks remain clickable in the output PDF</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h2
        class="mb-2 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wider uppercase"
        style="color: var(--color-accent)"
      >
        Supported fonts
      </h2>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Common Microsoft fonts render natively on Windows and Mac. On systems missing the
        original font, we automatically fall back to a metric-compatible clone:
      </p>
      <ul
        class="ml-5 mt-2 list-disc space-y-1 text-sm leading-relaxed"
        style="color: var(--color-muted)"
      >
        <li>Calibri → Carlito (Linux fallback)</li>
        <li>Arial / Helvetica → Liberation Sans / Arimo</li>
        <li>Times New Roman → Liberation Serif / Tinos</li>
        <li>Cambria → Caladea</li>
        <li>Courier New / Consolas → Liberation Mono / Cousine / Cascadia Code</li>
        <li>Georgia, Verdana, Tahoma, Trebuchet MS → DejaVu equivalents</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h2
        class="mb-2 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wider uppercase"
        style="color: var(--color-accent)"
      >
        Known limits (honest list)
      </h2>
      <ul
        class="ml-5 list-disc space-y-1 text-sm leading-relaxed"
        style="color: var(--color-muted)"
      >
        <li>
          Custom brand fonts that aren't installed on the user's system will substitute to the
          browser's default sans-serif or serif. Common Microsoft fonts (above) are handled.
        </li>
        <li>Complex multi-column layouts with fancy section breaks may shift slightly</li>
        <li>Embedded OLE objects (e.g. embedded Excel, ActiveX) won't render</li>
        <li>Tracked changes and comments are stripped (not visual content)</li>
        <li>Math equations rendered as images (works but may scale imperfectly)</li>
        <li>Older <code>.doc</code> format (use Word or LibreOffice to save as <code>.docx</code> first)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h2
        class="mb-2 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wider uppercase"
        style="color: var(--color-accent)"
      >
        Tip
      </h2>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        In the print dialog, set <strong>Destination</strong> to "Save as PDF" and
        <strong>Margins</strong> to "Default" for the best result. Most browsers remember this
        for next time.
      </p>
    </div>
  </aside>
</BaseLayout>
